        <fr:display-uri>002D</fr:display-uri>
        <fr:route>/lectures/002D/</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Proving I from S, K">Proving <html:strong>I</html:strong> from <html:strong>S</html:strong>, <html:strong>K</html:strong></fr:title>
        <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <html:table>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>1</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  (q \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  (p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  p \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>S</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>2</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  (q \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>3</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  p \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: 1, 2</html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>4</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>5</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: 3, 4</html:td>
</html:tr>
</html:table>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <html:p>This is a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex> in <html:strong>SK</html:strong>.
And since the theorems of <html:strong>SK</html:strong> are closed under substitution, this means that every instance of <html:strong>I</html:strong> has a proof in <html:strong>SK</html:strong>.
What does this tell us about the relationship between <html:strong>SK</html:strong> and <html:strong>SKI</html:strong>?</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
