                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:table>

<html:tr>
  <html:td />
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  (r \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  r \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: </html:td>
</html:tr>
</html:table>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <html:p>This is a proof of the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  (r \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  r \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>The form we'll call <html:strong>B</html:strong> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A \rightarrow  B) \rightarrow  (C \rightarrow  A) \rightarrow  C \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex>; note the relation between this form and the sentence proved above.
Every instance of <html:strong>B</html:strong> is also a <fr:link href="/lectures/001I/" title="Substitution instance" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/001I/" display-uri="001I" type="local">substitution instance</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  (r \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  r \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex>. 
</html:p>
